GIT
git branching strategies
git branch production rules:
A branch production rule is a set of rules or policies that define how the production branch is used, protected, and updated in Git.
In most teams, the production branch is called main or master, and it represents live, deployable code.
Production branch rules answer this question:
“What is allowed and not allowed on the production branch?”
These rules are enforced to:
Prevent accidental outages
Maintain stability
Ensure quality and security

✅ All changes must come through:

Pull Requests (PRs)
Merge Requests (MRs)

Before merging into production:

✅ Code review is mandatory
✅ Usually 1–2 approvals required

Only allow merge if:

✅ Build succeeds
✅ Tests pass
✅ Linting/security scans pass

Production branch must always be in a releasable state
This means:
No broken code
No half‑finished features
Feature flags for incomplete work

Limited Who Can Merge
Only:
Senior developers
Tech leads
DevOps engineers

If production breaks:
Create a hotfix/* branch from main
Fix the issue
Merge back into main (and develop if used)


CI/CD
---------
parametre pipe line:
A parametric pipeline is a CI/CD pipeline that is driven by parameters (inputs) instead of being completely hard‑coded.
A parametric pipeline lets you pass values (parameters) at runtime to control how the pipeline executes.
Traditional pipelines are often rigid:
One pipeline per environment
One pipeline per branch
One pipeline per use case

When a Pull Request is created, the pipeline runs and uses a parameter (ENV) to decide how it behaves.
A trigger is an event that automatically starts a pipeline.
In simple words:
A trigger tells the CI/CD system when to run a pipeline.
Without triggers, pipelines would only run manually.
trigger will happen in 4 diff ways:
push activity
parametrized way
pull request
schedule based
